  "text": "The passive avoidance task determines the ability of a mouse to remember a foot shock and to avoid learned stimuli [CITATION_1] . Briefly, apparatus used consisted of a shuttle box divided into two chambers of equal size, one illuminated and one dark, and both equipped with a grid floor. Training begins by placing a mouse in the light chamber opening the door to the dark chamber 20 seconds later. Because most mice prefer the dark chamber, experimental mice quickly enter the dark chamber. Training was repeated until the rats entered the dark compartment within 20 sec (training trial). After the training period, when a mouse entered the dark chamber, the door closed automatically and the mouse was delivered an electric foot shock (0.3 mA, 100 V, 3 s) after all four limbs had entered the dark chamber (acquisition trial). For actual testing, a mouse was placed in the light compartment 24 h after the acquisition trial and the time taken to enter the dark chamber (latency) was measured for 300 sec (retention trial). The following animal groups underwent passive avoidance testing; uninfected wild type (n = 10), uninfected Tg2576 (n = 10), and infected Tg2576 (n = 12) groups.",
